  "prompt": "what are the ethical principles and core values that govern the social work profession in America?",
  "response": "The social work profession in America is guided by a set of ethical principles and core values that outline the responsibilities of social workers towards individuals, families, groups, communities, and society as a whole. The National Association of Social Workers (NASW) encapsulates these principles in its **Code of Ethics**. Here are the key ethical principles and core values:\n\n### Core Values\n\n1. **Service**: Social workers prioritize helping others and placing the needs of their clients above their own. This includes providing services that benefit individuals, families, and communities.\n\n2. **Social Justice**: Social workers pursue social change, particularly on behalf of vulnerable and oppressed individuals and groups. They strive to promote policies that enhance the well-being of all people.\n\n3. **Dignity and Worth of the Person**: Social workers respect the intrinsic dignity and worth of every individual. They recognize that each person has the right to self-determination and advocate for their clients\u2019 perspectives.\n\n4. **Importance of Human Relationships**: Social workers understand that human relationships are central to human experience and are significant for personal development and well-being.\n\n5. **Integrity**: Social workers act in a trustworthy manner and uphold their professional commitments. They strive to be honest and transparent in their practice.\n\n6. **Competence**: Social workers continually seek to enhance their professional knowledge and skills. They are committed to providing services within their areas of competence and to engage in ongoing professional development.\n\n### Ethical Principles\n\n1. **Respect for Diversity**: Social workers recognize and celebrate the diversity of individuals and communities. They practice cultural competence and strive to be sensitive to the various backgrounds of the people they serve.\n\n2. **Relationship-Building**: Social workers establish meaningful relationships with clients to empower them and facilitate change. They recognize the importance of trust and collaboration.\n\n3. **Confidentiality**: Social workers protect client confidentiality and trust. They disclose information only with the consent of the clients or as mandated by law.\n\n4. **Dual Relationships and Boundaries**: Social workers maintain professional boundaries to avoid conflicts of interest and to protect the integrity of the client-social worker relationship.\n\n5. **Social Responsibility**: Social workers advocate for the rights and welfare of individuals and communities, promoting social reform and community justice.\n\n6. **Informed Consent**: Social workers inform clients about the nature and purpose of their services, ensuring that clients are fully aware of their rights and options.\n\nThe adherence to these core values and principles ensures that social workers conduct their practice with professionalism, compassion, and commitment to the ethical service of their clients and communities. The NASW Code of Ethics serves as a foundational document to guide social work practice in the United States.",
